**🚀 Swarm Update V2.2.0 — Deploying Monday**

🔥 **New Reward Mechanism**  
Swarm now uses a **fixed-percentage reward system** to create fair incentives and reduce registration spam.  

🏆 **Top Performer Allocations**  
🥇 1st: **20%** — Winner takes the largest share  
🥈 2nd: **15%** — Strong second place reward  
🥉 3rd: **12%** — Solid podium position  
4th: **8%** — Top tier completion  
5th: **4.25%** — Entry to elite group  

📊 **Ranks 6–100: Fair Decay Distribution**  
- 40.75% distributed using a hybrid linear-exponential decay  
- Even rank 100 still earns a small reward  
- Gradual decrease: each rank earns less than the one above it  
- Mid-tier miners (ranks 6–50) get **substantial rewards** while developing better models  
- Low-tier miners (ranks 51–100) get **some rewards** to keep going while improving their miners  

🚫 **Ranks 101+: 0% Rewards**  
- Only the top 100 miners receive emissions  
- Rank 101+ still keep their spot but earn nothing until they improve  

⚖️ **Zero-Score Redistribution**  
- Miners with **0 score** receive **0 rewards**  
- Their share is redistributed proportionally among performing miners  

---

**✅ Validator Collision Detection**  
After implementing **LiDAR**, miners now have a reliable way to avoid obstacles.  
To incentivize LiDAR usage, collision punishment has been reinforced — making obstacle avoidance more important than ever.  

**✅ New Formula for Time Score**  
Scoring now accounts for **maximum speed** and **distance to goal**, using the minimum possible time as a benchmark.  

**✅ Solid Platform**  
The landing platform is now solid. Drones must land on it, making the simulation more realistic.  

**✅ MAX_TILT_RAD = 0.7 → 1.047**  
Increased tilt angle allows for **faster speeds** and **sharper direction changes**.  

**✅ Goal Range: 10m → 30m**  
Goals can now appear further away, creating harder tasks and higher-quality models.  

**✅ Higher Obstacles**  
Maps now feature taller obstacles for more realistic and challenging navigation.  

---

⚠️ **Important Notice**  
This update brings back the **platform landing**.  
Miners will need to **retrain their models** to land on the platform, since existing models will not perform well with this change.  

---

**Deployment**  
This update will be deployed on **Monday**.  
You can already check the branch in our GitHub to see the changes in advance.   

This release is another step toward more **realistic, fair, and high-quality** drone simulations.  

**- Swarm Team**

@AliSaaf @miguelik Hi 👋🏻 I have a concern about the current LiDAR implementation. In the VEL mode we do not control the position of the drone. Because of that the drone can flight sideways and backwards too. Let’s imagine the situation where drone’s “forward” is the right side. The drone flights full speed to the goal and then sees an obstacle. It starts to break and because of this tilts backwards. As a result its right ray shoots into the sky and the obstacle “disappears”. The drone thinks it can fly forward again, but in a few steps it stabilises and its right ray again shows the obstacle, this time even closer. 
I see two possible way of solving this issue:
1. Put LiDAR on a gimbal, so the rays never tilts within some range. They only can do yaw in a horizontal plane. 
2. Add more rays. Each side has to have up and down variations. Like “forward_right_up”, “forward_right_down”, “right_up”, “right_down”, and so on.

Third option - switch from VEL to PID. As I understand in the PID mode we control throttle, roll, pitch and yaw. So the drone can always move forward facing. But the PID mode is more difficult for training...

From my experience the current LiDAR implementation is usable when the drone flies slow. But the truth is that about 40% seeds do not have obstacles on the way to the goal. So you can flight fast and sometimes avoid obstacles and you are a top miner with success rate around 50%.
